{0:10:25 - 0:11:37} {SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Thomas, scuttling with the crying infant through narrow streets past the back porches and the back stairs of the large old moldering antebellum houses...
{0:10:25 - 0:11:37} {SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 24 EXT. THE BACK OF AN OLD NEW ORLEANS HOUSE - NIGHT, 1918
{0:10:25 - 0:11:37} {SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He comes to an old three-story house with a screened porch, VOICES from inside... PEOPLE TALKING and LAUGHING... The Baby, soothed by the soft yellow light, by the music of the voices, by the house itself -- stops its mournful cry.
{0:10:25 - 0:11:37} {SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Thomas stops, catching his breath... He looks in through the back porch... the sounds of VOICES coming... Thomas quietly sets the baby on the back porch steps.
{0:10:25 - 0:11:37} {SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He takes out every last dollar he has, tucking the money inside the Baby's blanket... We can just see the figures of two people coming from inside... Thomas knocks on the weathered screen door... And his decision made, he turns, moving away from the house, leaving his child behind.
{0:10:25 - 0:11:37} {CHARACTER_NAME}: A WOMAN'S (V.O.)
{0:10:25 - 0:11:37} {DIALOGUE}: I could've sworn I heard somebody knockin'...
{0:10:25 - 0:11:37} {SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: When a young Black Woman, in a green dress, comes onto the porch... A thin, attractive woman, in her late 20s, with the sultry eyes of a lounge singer -- She's known as QUEENIE.
{0:10:25 - 0:11:37} {SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's followed by a handsome Black man, MR. WEATHERS -- that everyone calls TIZZY.
{0:10:25 - 0:11:37} {SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She looks out the door, and not seeing anything...
{0:10:25 - 0:11:37} {CHARACTER_NAME}: QUEENIE
{0:10:25 - 0:11:37} {DIALOGUE}: I guess not...
{0:10:25 - 0:11:37} {SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She stands for a moment taking in the night air...
